    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix integer truncation in Msg3 retransmission allocation for TDD configurations\n\n### Summary\nThe `get_Msg3_alloc_ret` function in the LTE scheduler had a critical bug where it failed to initialize the `subframe` output parameter in TDD mode. This caused downstream code to operate on uninitialized memory, leading to unpredictable scheduling behavior.\n\nAdditionally, the function signature used inconsistent types (`unsigned char`/`unsigned int`) compared to its declaration in the header files (`uint8_t`/`uint32_t`), potentially causing truncation on some platforms.\n\nThis fix ensures proper subframe assignment for all TDD configurations and aligns parameter types with header declarations.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/SCHED/phy_procedures_lte_common.c`: Fixed TDD subframe assignment logic and parameter types in `get_Msg3_alloc_ret`\n- The function now properly sets both `frame` and `subframe` outputs for all TDD configurations\n- Parameter types now match header file declarations\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the original issue:\n1. Configure UE in TDD mode with any TDD configuration (1, 3, 4, or 5)\n2. Trigger a Msg3 retransmission scheduling request\n3. Observe that `get_Msg3_alloc_ret` leaves `subframe` uninitialized\n4. Downstream scheduler uses garbage `subframe` value, causing incorrect UL resource allocation\n5. This may result in transmission failures or unexpected behavior in RA procedure handling\n\nThe fix ensures deterministic behavior by properly initializing the subframe allocation for Msg3 retransmissions in all TDD configurations.\n"
}